[src:snapshot-testing/characterization-test] In computer programming, a **characterization test** (also known as **Golden Master Testing**) is a means to describe (characterize) the **actual** behavior of an existing piece of software, and therefore protect existing behavior of legacy code against unintended changes via automated testing.
[src:snapshot-testing/characterization-test] This term was coined by Michael Feathers.
[src:snapshot-testing/characterization-test] The goal of characterization tests is to help developers verify that the modifications made to a reference version of a software system did not modify its behavior in unwanted or undesirable ways.
[src:snapshot-testing/characterization-test] They enable, and provide a safety net for, extending and refactoring code that does not have adequate unit tests.
[src:snapshot-testing/characterization-test] In James Bach's and Michael Bolton's classification of test oracles, this kind of testing corresponds to the **historical oracle**.
[src:snapshot-testing/characterization-test] In a sense, characterization testing inverts traditional testing: Traditional tests check that individual properties have certain values (whitelists them), whereas characterization testing checks that no properties have been changed (blacklisted).
[src:snapshot-testing/characterization-test] When creating a characterization test, one must observe what outputs occur for a given set of inputs.
[src:snapshot-testing/characterization-test] Given an observation that the legacy code gives a certain output based on given inputs, then a test can be written that asserts that the output of the legacy code matches the observed result for the given inputs.
[src:snapshot-testing/characterization-test] For example, if one observes that f(3.14) == 42, then this could be created as a characterization test.
[src:snapshot-testing/characterization-test] Then, after modifications to the system, the test can determine if the modifications caused changes in the results when given the same inputs.
[src:snapshot-testing/characterization-test] Unfortunately, as with any testing, it is generally not possible to create a characterization test for every possible input and output.
[src:snapshot-testing/characterization-test] As such, many people opt for either statement or branch coverage.
[src:snapshot-testing/characterization-test] Test writers must use their judgment to decide how much testing is appropriate.
[src:snapshot-testing/characterization-test] It is often sufficient to write characterization tests that only cover the specific inputs and outputs that are known to occur, paying special attention to edge cases.
[src:snapshot-testing/characterization-test] Unlike regression tests, to which they are very similar, characterization tests do not verify the *correct* behavior of the code, which can be impossible to determine.
[src:snapshot-testing/characterization-test] Instead they verify the behavior that was observed when they were written.
[src:snapshot-testing/characterization-test] Often no specification or test suite is available, leaving only characterization tests as an option, since the conservative path is to assume that the old behavior is the required behavior.
[src:snapshot-testing/characterization-test] Characterization tests are, essentially, change detectors.
[src:snapshot-testing/characterization-test] It is up to the person analyzing the results to determine if the detected change was expected and/or desirable, or unexpected and/or undesirable.
[src:snapshot-testing/characterization-test] One of the interesting aspects of characterization tests is that, since they are based on existing code, it's possible to generate some characterization tests automatically.
[src:snapshot-testing/characterization-test] An automated characterization test tool will exercise existing code with a wide range of relevant and/or random input values, record the output values (or state changes) and generate a set of characterization tests.
[src:snapshot-testing/characterization-test] When the generated tests are executed against a new version of the code, they will produce one or more failures/warnings if that version of the code has been modified in a way that changes a previously established behavior.
[src:snapshot-testing/characterization-test] When testing on the GUI level, characterization testing can be combined with intelligent monkey testing to create complex test cases that capture use cases and special cases thereof.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] Changes that may require regression testing include bug fixes, software enhancements, configuration changes, and even substitution of electronic components (hardware).
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] As regression test suites tend to grow with each found defect, test automation is frequently involved.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] Sometimes a change impact analysis is performed to determine an appropriate subset of tests (*non-regression analysis*).
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] As software is updated or changed, or reused on a modified target, emergence of new faults and/or re-emergence of old faults is quite common.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] Sometimes re-emergence occurs because a fix gets lost through poor revision control practices (or simple human error in revision control).
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] Often, a fix for a problem will be "fragile" in that it fixes the problem in the narrow case where it was first observed but not in more general cases which may arise over the lifetime of the software.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] Frequently, a fix for a problem in one area inadvertently causes a software bug in another area.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] It may happen that when a feature is redesigned some of the same mistakes that were made in the original implementation of the feature also occur in the redesign.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] In most software development situations, it is considered good coding practice, when a bug is located and fixed, to record a test that exposes the bug and re-run that test regularly after subsequent changes to the program.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] Although this may be done through manual testing procedures using programming techniques, it is often done using automated testing tools.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] Common strategies are to run such a system after every successful compile (for small projects), every night, or once a week.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] Those strategies can be automated by an external tool.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] Regression testing is an integral part of the extreme programming software development method.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] In this method, design documents are replaced by extensive, repeatable, and automated testing of the entire software package throughout each stage of the software development process.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] Regression testing is done after functional testing has concluded, to verify that the other functionalities are working.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] In the corporate world, regression testing has traditionally been performed by a software quality assurance team after the development team has completed work.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] However, defects found at this stage are the most costly to fix.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] This problem is being addressed by the rise of unit testing.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] Although developers have always written test cases as part of the development cycle, these test cases have generally been either functional tests or unit tests that verify only intended outcomes.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] Developer testing compels a developer to focus on unit testing and to include both positive and negative test cases.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] This technique checks all the test cases on the current program to check its integrity.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] Though it is expensive as it needs to re-run all the test cases, it ensures that there are no errors because of the modified code.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] Unlike Retest all, this technique runs a part of the test suite (owing to the cost of retest all) if the cost of selecting the part of the test suite is less than the Retest all technique.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] Prioritize the test cases so as to increase a test suite's rate of fault detection.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] Test case prioritization techniques schedule test cases so that the test cases that are higher in priority are executed before the test cases that have a lower priority.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] This technique is a hybrid of regression test selection and test case prioritization.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] Regression testing is performed when changes are made to the existing functionality of the software or if there is a bug fix in the software.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] Regression testing can be achieved through multiple approaches; if a *test all* approach is followed, it provides certainty that the changes made to the software have not affected the existing functionalities, which are unaltered.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] In agile software development—where the software development life cycles are very short, resources are scarce, and changes to the software are very frequent—regression testing might introduce a lot of unnecessary overhead.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] Regression testing can be used not only for testing the *correctness* of a program but often also for tracking the quality of its output.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] For instance, in the design of a compiler, regression testing could track the code size and the time it takes to compile and execute the test suite cases.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] — Fred Brooks, *The Mythical Man Month*, p.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] Regression tests can be done at any level, from unit through to system integration.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] Functional tests exercise the complete program with various inputs.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] These tests are often automated due to the need for repetition, and may be done by test tools that are not part of the compiler suite.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] Non-functional tests assess aspects such as performance, security, or reliability.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] Conducting non-functional regression tests presents additional challenges.
[src:snapshot-testing/regression-testing] For example, detecting changes in performance is often statistically complex, while security issues typically arise from vulnerabilities in the software ecosystem rather than from individual code changes.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] Snapshot tests are a very useful tool whenever you want to make sure your UI does not change unexpectedly.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] A typical snapshot test case renders a UI component, takes a snapshot, then compares it to a reference snapshot file stored alongside the test.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] The test will fail if the two snapshots do not match: either the change is unexpected, or the reference snapshot needs to be updated to the new version of the UI component.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] A similar approach can be taken when it comes to testing your React components.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] Instead of rendering the graphical UI, which would require building the entire app, you can use a test renderer to quickly generate a serializable value for your React component.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] The snapshot artifact should be committed alongside code changes, and reviewed as part of your code review process.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] Jest uses pretty-format to make snapshots human-readable during code review.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] On subsequent test runs, Jest will compare the rendered output with the previous snapshot.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] If they don't match, either the test runner found a bug in your code (in the `<Link>` component in this case) that should be fixed, or the implementation has changed and the snapshot needs to be updated.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] The snapshot is directly scoped to the data you render – in our example the `<Link>` component with `page` prop passed to it.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] This implies that even if any other file has missing props (say, `App.js`) in the `<Link>` component, it will still pass the test as the test doesn't know the usage of `<Link>` component and it's scoped only to the `Link.js`.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] Also, rendering the same component with different props in other snapshot tests will not affect the first one, as the tests don't know about each other.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] More information on how snapshot testing works and why we built it can be found on the release blog post.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] We recommend reading this blog post to get a good sense of when you should use snapshot testing.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] We also recommend watching this egghead video on Snapshot Testing with Jest.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] It's straightforward to spot when a snapshot test fails after a bug has been introduced.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] When that happens, go ahead and fix the issue and make sure your snapshot tests are passing again.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] Now, let's talk about the case when a snapshot test is failing due to an intentional implementation change.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] One such situation can arise if we intentionally change the address the Link component in our example is pointing to.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] Since we just updated our component to point to a different address, it's reasonable to expect changes in the snapshot for this component.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] Our snapshot test case is failing because the snapshot for our updated component no longer matches the snapshot artifact for this test case.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] To resolve this, we will need to update our snapshot artifacts.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] Go ahead and accept the changes by running the above command.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] You may also use the equivalent single-character `-u` flag to re-generate snapshots if you prefer.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] This will re-generate snapshot artifacts for all failing snapshot tests.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] If we had any additional failing snapshot tests due to an unintentional bug, we would need to fix the bug before re-generating snapshots to avoid recording snapshots of the buggy behavior.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] If you'd like to limit which snapshot test cases get re-generated, you can pass an additional `--testNamePattern` flag to re-record snapshots only for those tests that match the pattern.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] You can try out this functionality by cloning the snapshot example, modifying the `Link` component, and running Jest.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] Once you enter Interactive Snapshot Mode, Jest will step you through the failed snapshots one test at a time and give you the opportunity to review the failed output.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] Inline snapshots behave identically to external snapshots (`.snap` files), except the snapshot values are written automatically back into the source code.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] This means you can get the benefits of automatically generated snapshots without having to switch to an external file to make sure the correct value was written.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] You can even update the snapshots with `--updateSnapshot` or using the `u` key in `--watch` mode.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] By default, Jest handles the writing of snapshots into your source code.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] However, if you're using prettier in your project, Jest will detect this and delegate the work to prettier instead (including honoring your configuration).
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] Often there are fields in the object you want to snapshot which are generated (like IDs and Dates).
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] For these cases, Jest allows providing an asymmetric matcher for any property.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] If the case concerns a string not an object then you need to replace random part of that string on your own before testing the snapshot.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] Other ways this can be done is using the snapshot serializer or mocking the library responsible for generating the random part of the code you're snapshotting.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] Snapshots are a fantastic tool for identifying unexpected interface changes within your application – whether that interface is an API response, UI, logs, or error messages.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] As with any testing strategy, there are some best-practices you should be aware of, and guidelines you should follow, in order to use them effectively.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] Commit snapshots and review them as part of your regular code review process.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] This means treating snapshots as you would any other type of test or code in your project.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] Ensure that your snapshots are readable by keeping them focused, short, and by using tools that enforce these stylistic conventions.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] The goal is to make it easy to review snapshots in pull requests, and fight against the habit of regenerating snapshots when test suites fail instead of examining the root causes of their failure.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] Running the same tests multiple times on a component that has not changed should produce the same results every time.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] You're responsible for making sure your generated snapshots do not include platform specific or other non-deterministic data.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] For example, if you have a Clock component that uses `Date.now()`, the snapshot generated from this component will be different every time the test case is run.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] Now, every time the snapshot test case runs, `Date.now()` will return `1482363367071` consistently.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] This will result in the same snapshot being generated for this component regardless of when the test is run.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] Always strive to use descriptive test and/or snapshot names for snapshots.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] The best names describe the expected snapshot content.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] This makes it easier for reviewers to verify the snapshots during review, and for anyone to know whether or not an outdated snapshot is the correct behavior before updating.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] No, as of Jest 20, snapshots in Jest are not automatically written when Jest is run in a CI system without explicitly passing `--updateSnapshot`.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] It is expected that all snapshots are part of the code that is run on CI and since new snapshots automatically pass, they should not pass a test run on a CI system.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] It is recommended to always commit all snapshots and to keep them in version control.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] Yes, all snapshot files should be committed alongside the modules they are covering and their tests.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] They should be considered part of a test, similar to the value of any other assertion in Jest.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] In fact, snapshots represent the state of the source modules at any given point in time.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] In this way, when the source modules are modified, Jest can tell what changed from the previous version.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] It can also provide a lot of additional context during code review in which reviewers can study your changes better.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] React and React Native components are a good use case for snapshot testing.
[src:snapshot-testing/snapshot-testing] However, snapshots can capture any serializable value and should be used anytime the goal is testing whether the output is correct.
