[src:snapshot-testing/unit-testing] Using unit-tests as a design specification has one significant advantage over other design methods: The design document (the unit-tests themselves) can itself be used to verify the implementation.
[src:snapshot-testing/unit-testing] The tests will never pass unless the developer implements a solution according to the design.
[src:snapshot-testing/unit-testing] Unit testing lacks some of the accessibility of a diagrammatic specification such as a UML diagram, but they may be generated from the unit test using automated tools.
[src:snapshot-testing/unit-testing] Most modern languages have free tools (usually available as extensions to IDEs).
